{"item":"castle","set":{"castleId":108,"townId":0,"active":1,"name_LO":"\u0417\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043a \u00ab\u0421\u0435\u043d\u0442-\u041c\u0456\u043a\u043b\u043e\u0448\u00bb (\u0427\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0434\u0456\u0457\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439)","settlement_HU":"Beregszentmikl\u00f3s","settlement_LO":"\u0427\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0434\u0456\u0439\u043e\u0432\u043e","address":"\u0432\u0443\u043b. \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430, 53\u0411, Chynadiiovo, Zakarpattia Oblast, Ukrajna, 89640","listorder":3,"gps_lat":"48.4847610000","gps_long":"22.8311150000","oldcounty":21,"country":3,"division":9,"cond":2,"entrance":1,"varaklink":"https:\/\/varak.hu\/latnivalo\/index\/1851-Szentmiklos-Beregszentmiklos-varkastely\/","homepage":"http:\/\/www.stmiklos.com\/","openinghours":"http:\/\/www.stmiklos.com\/?page_id=35","picture":"\u003Ca title=\u0022\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0456\u0439 \u0412\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \/ CC BY-SA (https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-sa\/4.0)\u0022 href=\u0022https:\/\/commons.wikimedia.org\/wiki\/File:%D0%97%D0%B0%D0%BC%D0%BE%D0%BA_%D1%83_%D0%A7%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%96%D0%B9%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE_%D0%A7%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%96%D0%B9%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE.jpg\u0022\u003E\u003Cimg width=\u0022512\u0022 alt=\u0022\u0417\u0430\u043c\u043e\u043a \u0443 \u0427\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0434\u0456\u0439\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0427\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0434\u0456\u0439\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0022 src=\u0022https:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/e\/e4\/%D0%97%D0%B0%D0%BC%D0%BE%D0%BA_%D1%83_%D0%A7%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%96%D0%B9%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE_%D0%A7%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%96%D0%B9%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE.jpg\/512px-%D0%97%D0%B0%D0%BC%D0%BE%D0%BA_%D1%83_%D0%A7%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%96%D0%B9%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE_%D0%A7%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%96%D0%B9%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE.jpg\u0022\u003E\u003C\/a\u003E","picture_ref":"\u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/commons.wikimedia.org\/wiki\/File:%D0%97%D0%B0%D0%BC%D0%BE%D0%BA_%D1%83_%D0%A7%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%96%D0%B9%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE_%D0%A7%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%96%D0%B9%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE.jpg\u0022 title=\u0022via Wikimedia Commons\u0022\u003E\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0456\u0439 \u0412\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439\u003C\/a\u003E \/ \u003Ca href=\u0022https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-sa\/4.0\u0022\u003ECC BY-SA\u003C\/a\u003E","name":"Szentmikl\u00f3s Castle","georegion":"Latorca Valley","description":"","nameorigin":"","history":"#1|@#3|@early 13th century|The settlement was owned by Simon, the son-in-low of Ban B\u00e1nk.@1214|The castle was confiscated from Simon due to the succesfull attempt on the life of Queen Gertrude of Merania, the wife of King Andrew II of Hungary. Since the king favored the German relatives of Queen Gertrude over the Hungarian nobles, a group of the aristocrats (isp\u00e1n Peter, Simon of the Kacsics clan and Simon, the son-in-low of n\u00e1dor B\u00e1nk) conspired against her. The assassination was carried out during King Andrew's campaign against Halych. Gertrude was killed on the first suitable occasion during a royal hunt in the Pilis Mountains. Katona J\u00f3zsef's play and Erkel Ferenc's opera both of the same title (B\u00e1nk b\u00e1n) are based on this story. The children of King Andrew II and Queen Gertrude were King B\u00e9la IV and Saint Elisabeth of Hungary, one of the most venerated Hungarian saints.@#5|@late 14th century|The ancestors of the Per\u00e9nyi family owned the settlement.@1403|King Sigismund of Hungary allowed Per\u00e9nyi Imre to build a fortified manor in Szentmikl\u00f3s. This castle and manor was owned by the Per\u00e9nyi family until 1542.@#8|@#9|@#10|@1578 \u2013 1585|The castle was reconstructed.@1600|Telegdi Zsigmond owned the castle.@1612|Ny\u00e1ri Istv\u00e1n received the castle.@1649|King Ferdinand III of Hungary gave the castle and the lordship to L\u00f3nyai Zsigmond and his successors. The widow of L\u00f3nyai Zsigmond was married by R\u00e1k\u00f3czi L\u00e1szl\u00f3, who acquired the lordships of Munk\u00e1cs and Szentmikl\u00f3s for his family this way.@January 1657|Prince R\u00e1k\u00f3czi Gy\u00f6rgy II of Transylvania launched a campaign against Poland in alliance with Carl X Gustaf of Sweden. His goal was to take the Polish crown and unite the Hungarian-Polish-Wallachian forces against the Turks. The campaign started successfully, the Prince even occupied Krak\u00f3w and Warsawa, but afterwards the King of Sweden let him down. The vengeful Poles led by Marshall Jerzy Lubomirski broke into northern Transylvania.@1657|After the unsuccesful Polish campaign of Prince R\u00e1k\u00f3czi Gy\u00f6rgy II of Transylvania, the Poles plundered the castle of Szentmikl\u00f3s as well.@1669|Emperor Leopold I allowed the R\u00e1k\u00f3czi family to take over the lordship of Szentmikl\u00f3s from the Esterh\u00e1zy family for 65,000 thaler (silver coin).@1673|It was mentioned as the possession of the widow of R\u00e1k\u00f3czi Ferenc I, B\u00e1thory Zs\u00f3fia. With the death of B\u00e1thory Zs\u00f3fia (1680), the estate was acquired by her daughter-in-law Zr\u00ednyi Ilona for the benefit of her children. R\u00e1k\u00f3czi Ferenc II frequently visited the castle of Szentmikl\u00f3s on his hunts.@#25|@#26|@#27|@february 19, 1711|Prince R\u00e1k\u00f3czi Ferenc II spent his last night in his Hungarian homeland in the castle, before leaving for Poland.@after 1711|After the Peace of Szatm\u00e1r, the estates of R\u00e1k\u00f3czi were managed by the Treasury.@1726|Emperor Charles VI gave Szentmikl\u00f3s to Count Sch\u00f6nborn Lot\u00e1r Ferenc together with Munk\u00e1cs. His family and their descendents owned the castle afterwards.&"},"language":"en","region":"ukraine","regionid":3,"offer":[{"id":"101","settlement_HU":"Szuhabaranka","settlement_LO":"\u0411\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044c\u043a\u0430","gps_lat":"48.4105640000